nks":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5287"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2023-05-08T23:53:34+09:30","updatedAt":"2023-12-03T16:46:46+10:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2023-12-03T16:46:46+10:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-23 15:57:42"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12844"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"8676"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"25468"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"446"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8996"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9403"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10259"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"25468"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"40771","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/40771"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents with a four day history of diarrhoea and mild generalised abdominal pain. He feels increasingly fatigued and has noticed that his urine has become dark. He has also felt feverish and has taken several paracetamol tablets which was helpful. He had several take-out meals in the days before his symptoms started, but none of his other friends who had the same meals are unwell. He is originally from Iran, has not travelled recently and has received all his immunisations. He reports his uncle had a history of some sort of problem with his blood and dark coloured urine for which he was hospitalised on a few occasions, but he cannot remember the details.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination he has scleral icterus and appears to be jaundiced. His blood pressure is 129/76 mmHg, pulse 115/min, temperature 37.6\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC, respiratory rate 15/min and SpO\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E 99% on room air. The rest of the physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["G6PD deficiency","Hepatitis A","Cholangitis","Paracetamol toxicity","Gilbert syndrome"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGiven the history of dark urine and an examination finding of jaundice on the background of a family history suggestive of a red cell abnormality, the presentation is consistent with a haemolytic crisis associated with \u003Cstrong\u003EG6PD \u003C/strong\u003Edeficiency. The triggers for haemolytic anaemia in patients with G6PD deficiency can include foods (e.g. fava beans), infections or medications (e.g. rasburicase)\u003Ca href=\u0022https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26417175/\u0022\u003E 1\u003C/a\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EG6PD deficiency \u003C/strong\u003Eis an X-linked recessive disorder, like haemophilia and colour blindness. As males only have one X chromosome, they are more likely than women to present with G6PD deficiency symptoms, such as anaemia, jaundice, dark urine and splenomegaly. The stem states that the patient\u0027s uncle (male) experienced similar symptoms in the past, suggesting an inherited condition that is most likely X-linked.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis A \u003C/strong\u003Eis an important differential diagnosis in this patient and does explain most of his symptoms but it would be unlikely to present so quickly as it has an incubation period of 3-5 weeks\u003Ca href=\u0022https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6120688/\u0022\u003E 2\u003C/a\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECholangitis is \u003C/strong\u003Echaracteristically described by Charcot\u0027s triad of abdominal pain, fever and jaundice but would not explain his predominant diarrhoea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParacetamol toxicity \u003C/strong\u003Eis a possibility and an important consideration but the lack of nausea and vomiting makes this less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGilbert syndrome \u003C/strong\u003Eis a possibility but would not have features consistent with haemolytic anaemia such as darkened urine.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Consider pre-hepatic causes of jaundice in patients presenting with gastrointestinal symptoms and have a known family or personal history of red cell abnormalities (e.g. G6PD Deficiency)"],"references":["Bubp J, Jen M, Matuszewski K. Caring for Glucose-6-Phosphate Dehydrogenase (G6PD)-Deficient Patients: Implications for Pharmacy. P T. 2015 Sep;40(9):572-4. PMID: 26417175; PMCID: PMC4571844.","Shin, E. C., \u0026 Jeong, S. H. (2018). Natural History, Clinical Manifestations, and Pathogenesis of Hepatitis A. Cold Spring Harbor perspectives in medicine, 8(9), a031708. https://doi.org/10.1101/cshperspect.a031708"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"25468"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12844"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"25468","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/25468"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-12-03T16:45:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2023-12-03T16:45:34+10:30","number":10,"notes":"","plagiarismCheckedAt":null,"plagiarismScore":null,"plagiarismReportUrl":null},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5287"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"40771"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9"}},"generation":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,